{"title_page": "Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Allan Sherman]]\n| album      = [[My Son, the Nut]]\n| B-side     = (Rag Mop) Rat Fink\n| released   = [[1963 in music|August 1963]]\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Novelty song]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=47}}\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| writer     = [[Allan Sherman]], [[Lou Busch]], [[Amilcare Ponchielli]]\n| producer   = Jimmy Hilliard\n| prev_title = [[The Twelve Gifts of Christmas]]\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp) (1964 Version)\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n\"'''Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)'''\" is a [[novelty song]] by [[Allan Sherman]] and [[Lou Busch]], based on letters of complaint Allan received from his son Robert while Robert attended Camp Champlain, a [[summer camp]] in [[Westport, New York|Westport]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2003-aug-16-et-lieberman16-story.html| title = The Boy in Camp Granada| work=Lifestyle|accessdate = 2008-02-09| date =  August 16, 2003| author=Paul Lieberman|publisher = LA Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the song was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] for being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite news |date=March 25, 2020 |title=National Recording Registry Class Produces Ultimate 'Stay at Home' Playlist |url=https://loc.gov/item/prn-20-023/|work=[[Library of Congress]]|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==The song==\nThe song is a [[parody]] that complains about the fictional \"Camp Granada\" and is set to the tune of [[Amilcare Ponchielli]]'s ''[[Dance of the Hours]]''. The name derives from the first lines:\n:''Hello Muddah, hello Fadduh.<br/> Here I am at Camp Granada.<br/> Camp is very entertaining.<br/> And they say we'll have some fun if it stops raining''.\n\nThe lyrics go on to describe unpleasant, dangerous, and tragic developments, such as fellow campers going missing or contracting deadly illnesses. He asks how his \"precious little brother\" is doing, and begs to be taken home, afraid of being left out in the forest and fearing getting eaten by a bear, promising to behave, and even letting his aunt Bertha hug and kiss him. At the end, he notes that the rain has stopped and fun activities have begun (such as swimming, sailing, and baseball), and asks his parents to \"kindly disregard this letter\".\n\n==Success==\n\nThe song scored #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] list for three weeks beginning on August 24, 1963.  It was kept from #1 by both: [[Fingertips]] by \"Little\" [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]] by [[The Angels (American group)|The Angels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1963-08-24|title=The Hot 100 Chart|website=Billboard|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020}}</ref>  Sherman wrote a new 'back at Camp Granada' version, \"Hello Mudduh, Hello Fadduh!\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kafejo.com/muziko/misc/granada.htm|title=Kafejo.com : Camp Granada|website=www.kafejo.com|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020}}</ref> for a May 27, 1964, performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]''.in the sequel, It begins with a whistle, with Sherman spelling out the name of \"Granada\", and saying \"Blagh!!!\", before he sings. he is back in the camp, where some things have improved, such as the food, and some new issues arrive, such as not knowing where the bunk, trunk, or where the skunk is, or that the showers outside have thin doors, wishing that they would be moved indoors, instead. The song also states that the comedian Lenny Bruce was to make a camp appearance. Sherman wants to stay, loving Granada for several things including the poker games. this time, Sherman is taking care of his younger brother, who is immature. the younger brother gets up early each morning to go to the Quicksand, (toilet). the final line states that he was homesick, but that he got over it, and that he's like all of the other boys \"Except his bed is wetter\". Sherman wrote a third version for, and acted in, a 1965 TV commercial for a board game about [[Camp Granada]], a \"real rotten camp\".<ref name=LikeTelevision>{{cite web | url = http://tesla.liketelevision.com/liketelevision/tuner.php?channel=578&format=tv&theme=toyland | title = LikeTelevision - Camp Granada by Milton Bradley| work=liketelevision ...only better|accessdate = 2008-02-09| date =  | publisher = LikeTelevision}}</ref>  The original version also reached #9 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Pop-Standard Singles chart]].<ref>{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |authorlink= Joel Whitburn |year= 1993 |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961\u20131993 |publisher= Record Research |page=217}}</ref>\nThe song hit number one in Hong Kong, which does not have any summer camps.\nThe song won the [[Grammy Awards of 1964#Comedy|1964 Grammy Award for Best Comedy Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1964-216.html |title=Grammy Award Nominees 1964 \u2013 Grammy Award Winners 1964 |last=|first=|date=|website=Awardsandshows.com |accessdate=10 August 2019 }}</ref>  It was played frequently on the ''[[Dr. Demento]] Show'' and is featured on the [[Rhino Records]] compilation album, ''Dr. Demento 20th Anniversary Collection''.  It was played over the end credits of the 1993 film [[Indian Summer (1993 film)|Indian Summer]] and was briefly heard in [[The Simpsons]] episode [[Marge Be Not Proud]] after Bart Simpson switches the family's answering machine cassette tapes.  It was featured in the final scene of [[The King of Queens]] episode \"Tube Stakes\", during which main character Arthur Spooner performs his morning stretches.\n\n==Translations==\n\nVariations of the song include adaptations in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] (\"Brev fr\u00e5n kolonien\" by [[Cornelis Vreeswijk]]), [[Finnish language|Finnish]] (\"Terve mutsi, terve fatsi, t\u00e4ss\u00e4 teid\u00e4n ihmelapsi\") and [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] (\"Brev fra leier'n\" by [[Birgit Str\u00f8m]]). The Finnish version is included in the Finnish Boy Scouts' songbook. The Swedish version notably does not revolve around the camper hating the camp, but is about the kids running roughshod over it and having run off all the counselors, one of whom has committed suicide after they let a snake into the mess hall, and the organizer of the camp being arrested by police after the kids start a forest fire. The song begins with the boy writing the letter asking his parents to send more money, because he has lost all his pocket money playing dice with the other campers. The song then ends with the boy having to wrap up the letter as he is about to join the others in burning down the neighboring camp lodge.\n\nThe Dutch version ''Brief uit la Courtine'' sung bij [[Rijk de Gooyer]] is not about a children's summer camp, but about a soldier in the Dutch army camp at [[La Courtine]], France.\n\nThe Austrian comedian Paul Pizzera presented a German interpretation with the name \u201cJungscharlager\u201d in 2013.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Camp Runamuck]]'', a sitcom (1965\u201366) loosely inspired by the song\n* [[Camp Granada]], a 1965 board game inspired by the song\n* [[Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah! (book)|''Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah!'' (book)]], a 2004 children's book based on the song\n* [[Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah! (musical)|''Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh!'' (musical)]], a musical revue inspired by the song\n* [[Sandra Gould]], who released a response novelty recording, set to the same music, entitled \"Hello Melvin (This Is Mama)\".\n* [[Perrey and Kingsley]] did an instrumental version, called Countdown at 6, on [[The_In_Sound_from_Way_Out!_(Perrey_and_Kingsley_album)|The In Sound From Way Out]]. Like 'Hello Muhhah, Hello Faddah!,' it is based on Amilcare Ponchielli's \"Dance of the Hours\".\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MusicBrainz work|mbid=0c78a610-72e4-450a-992b-73a786234586|name=Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)}}\n\n{{Allan Sherman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh}}\n[[Category:1963 singles]]\n[[Category:Allan Sherman songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]\n[[Category:Musical parodies]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Fiction about summer camps]]\n[[Category:Songs about children]]\n[[Category:Songs about parenthood]]\n[[Category:Jewish comedy and humor]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Allan Sherman]]\n| album      = [[My Son, the Nut]]\n| B-side     = (Rag Mop) Rat Fink\n| released   = [[1963 in music|August 1963]]\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Novelty song]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=47}}\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| writer     = [[Allan Sherman]], [[Lou Busch]], [[Amilcare Ponchielli]]\n| producer   = Jimmy Hilliard\n| prev_title = [[The Twelve Gifts of Christmas]]\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp) (1964 Version)\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n\"'''Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)'''\" is a [[novelty song]] by [[Allan Sherman]] and [[Lou Busch]], based on letters of complaint Allan received from his son Robert while Robert attended Camp Champlain, a [[summer camp]] in [[Westport, New York|Westport]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2003-aug-16-et-lieberman16-story.html| title = The Boy in Camp Granada| work=Lifestyle|accessdate = 2008-02-09| date =  August 16, 2003| author=Paul Lieberman|publisher = LA Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the song was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]] for being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite news |date=March 25, 2020 |title=National Recording Registry Class Produces Ultimate 'Stay at Home' Playlist |url=https://loc.gov/item/prn-20-023/|work=[[Library of Congress]]|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==The song==\nThe song is a [[parody]] that complains about the fictional \"Camp Granada\" and is set to the tune of [[Amilcare Ponchielli]]'s ''[[Dance of the Hours]]''. The name derives from the first lines:\n:''Hello Muddah, hello Fadduh.<br/> Here I am at Camp Granada.<br/> Camp is very entertaining.<br/> And they say we'll have some fun if it stops raining''.\n\nThe lyrics go on to describe unpleasant, dangerous, and tragic developments, such as fellow campers going missing or contracting deadly illnesses. He asks how his \"precious little brother\" is doing, and begs to be taken home, afraid of being left out in the forest and fearing getting eaten by a bear, promising to behave, and even letting his aunt Bertha hug and kiss him. At the end, he notes that the rain has stopped and fun activities have begun (such as swimming, sailing, and baseball), and asks his parents to \"kindly disregard this letter\".\n\n==Success==\n\nThe song scored #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] list for three weeks beginning on August 24, 1963.  It was kept from #1 by both: [[Fingertips]] by \"Little\" [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]] by [[The Angels (American group)|The Angels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1963-08-24|title=The Hot 100 Chart|website=Bill