racter Arthur Spooner performs his morning stretches.\n\n==Translations==\n\nVariations of the song include adaptations in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] (\"Brev fr\u00e5n kolonien\" by [[Cornelis Vreeswijk]]), [[Finnish language|Finnish]] (\"Terve mutsi, terve fatsi, t\u00e4ss\u00e4 teid\u00e4n ihmelapsi\") and [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] (\"Brev fra leier'n\" by [[Birgit Str\u00f8m]]). The Finnish version is included in the Finnish Boy Scouts' songbook. The Swedish version notably does not revolve around the camper hating the camp, but is about the kids running roughshod over it and having run off all the counselors, one of whom has committed suicide after they let a snake into the mess hall, and the organizer of the camp being arrested by police after the kids start a forest fire. The song begins with the boy writing the letter asking his parents to send more money, because he has lost all his pocket money playing dice with the other campers. The song then ends with the boy having to wrap up the letter as he is about to join the others in burning down the neighboring camp lodge.\n\nThe Dutch version ''Brief uit la Courtine'' sung bij [[Rijk de Gooyer]] is not about a children's summer camp, but about a soldier in the Dutch army camp at [[La Courtine]], France.\n\nThe Austrian comedian Paul Pizzera presented a German interpretation with the name \u201cJungscharlager\u201d in 2013.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Camp Runamuck]]'', a sitcom (1965\u201366) loosely inspired by the song\n* [[Camp Granada]], a 1965 board game inspired by the song\n* [[Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah! (book)|''Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah!'' (book)]], a 2004 children's book based on the song\n* [[Hello Muddah, Hello Faddah! (musical)|''Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh!'' (musical)]], a musical revue inspired by the song\n* [[Sandra Gould]], who released a response novelty recording, set to the same music, entitled \"Hello Melvin (This Is Mama)\".\n* [[Perrey and Kingsley]] did an instrumental version, called Countdown at 6, on [[The_In_Sound_from_Way_Out!_(Perrey_and_Kingsley_album)|The In Sound From Way Out]]. Like 'Hello Muhhah, Hello Faddah!,' it is based on Amilcare Ponchielli's \"Dance of the Hours\".\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MusicBrainz work|mbid=0c78a610-72e4-450a-992b-73a786234586|name=Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh (A Letter from Camp)}}\n\n{{Allan Sherman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hello Muddah, Hello Fadduh}}\n[[Category:1963 singles]]\n[[Category:Allan Sherman songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]\n[[Category:Musical parodies]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Fiction about summer camps]]\n[[Category:Songs about children]]\n[[Category:Songs about parenthood]]\n[[Category:Jewish comedy and humor]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1012:b010:df93:86c3:15c3:7621:8a9f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSuccess)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hello_Muddah,_Hello_Fadduh_(A_Letter_from_Camp)"}
